Germany: a budget fetish that costs a lot.
FRANKFURT – The European Central Bank (ECB) is under fierce attack in Germany, a country that has long prided itself on defending the principle of the independence of the central bank.
It was Germany that insisted that this principle be incorporated into the criteria enunciated by the Maastricht Treaty, which set the conditions for membership in the European Monetary Union.
For many members of the Economic and Monetary Union (EMU), the decision to grant independence to their central bank in order to join the euro zone involved a change in political regime.
Thus the independence of the Bank of France, during the ratification referendum of the Maastricht Treaty, in 1992, was one of the strongest arguments of the campaign against EU membership.
In today's Germany, it has become a common practice, if you will, to exert pressure on the central bank.
For several months now, even the Minister of Finance, Wolfgang Schaüble, regularly comments on the monetary policy of the European Central Bank (ECB).
Schaüble's interventions target the very heart of what constitutes the independence of the central bank.
If he doesn't aim to redefine the goal of monetary policy (that 'price norm', in the old jargon of the Bundesbank), he nonetheless freely offers his advice on the tools the ECB should use and how it should use them to achieve such a goal.
We know of precedents.
In 1998, Oskar Lafontaine, then German Finance Minister, advised the first president of the ECB, Wim Duisenberg, on how to conduct monetary policy (Lafontaine's goal was ultimately to create a target zone for exchange rates).
Duisenberg, with typically Dutch laconicism, replied that it was nothing out of the ordinary for a politician to share his opinion on monetary policy (in Germany, it was absolutely unusual). "Still – he added –, it would be completely abnormal to take his suggestions into account."
I'm ready to help. What is the sentence to be translated?
Respect for the independence of monetary policy has long been a central element of Germany's stability culture.
The founding act of the Bundesbank's reputation for strict independence, achieved by its refusal to comply with the exhortations of Chancellor Konrad Adenauer, who wanted it to curb the rise in interest rates in 1956.
At that time, France did not see things in the same way.
Charles de Gaulle was on the point of creating the Fifth Republic, with a Bank of France that answered to the Minister of Finance.
But those were different times.
Following the various crises that have shaken the UEM, monetary policy has increasingly tended to replace fiscal policy.
Would the old dogma have become antiquated ?
Europe remains very vulnerable; the median resident of the EU has already lost ten years, and what is even more alarming, we are close to a critical situation.
The United States, after all, do better.
Notwithstanding a difficult-to-manage political deadlock, they have managed to tackle the macroeconomic problem (global demand weakness) they faced by launching expansionary fiscal and monetary policies.
The United States also managed their banking problems better, which, at the start, were much more severe than in Europe.
There is obviously a strong interaction between the measures that can be taken in both areas.
The stronger an economy is, the more profitable its banks are and the better equipped they are to fulfill their function: financing the economy.
But the independence of the ECB is less threatened by the good advice of a Finance Minister than by the lack of support from the population.
In fact, the famous autonomy of the Bundesbank rested less on its legal status than on the unwavering support (justified by its performance) of German citizens.
It's exactly the opposite with the ECB.
Voices are being heard, particularly in Germany, calling for it to be subjected to more pressure.
But the greatest threat to the ECB's independence is the unbearable burden that weighs on its shoulders.
The less the budget policy is solicited to stabilize production, the more central banks are de facto forced to take on this objective (unless, of course, they are designed to let nature take its course, and allow the economy to slip into stagnation, or worse).
The political result of this sequence is a very clear regression towards nationalism, on both right and left, in all UEM countries, including Germany.
The rise of nationalism is almost a logical corollary of the policies pursued.
She is endogenous.
And there too, Germany is leading the dance, with its obsession with the black zero, budgetary balance, against wind and tide.
In Germany, deficits are viewed poorly, not only from an arithmetic but also a moral perspective, even if this defies sound economic sense and appears to be clientelism.
At the end of the 19th century, the main German specialists in public finance, including Albert Schäffle and Adolph Wagner, forged a 'golden rule' according to which current expenditures must be financed, on average, by current revenues.
Public expenditures, and the resources they require, are justified by their utility.
This means that investments aimed at improving productivity – capital expenditures – can be funded with debt, the servicing of which is secured by growth in earnings and the associated revenue base.
This classic line of conduct has been institutionalised in a useful concept: the distinction between current expenses and investment expenses, which is still practiced at the municipal level in Germany (and Austria).
It's crucial, because in Germany, around 50% of public sector investment spending are managed at this level (share decreasing, since the municipal share was two-thirds at the beginning of the 1990s).
These expenses are consistent with the support of competitiveness of German small and medium-sized enterprises (Mittelstand).
Compared to the beginning of the 1990s at constant prices, investment expenditures have fallen by about 15%.
They have been insufficient for maintaining the capital stock for more than a decade.
If this isn't how we prepare the future, that's how we undermine productivity and prosperity.
In short, the black zero goes against the intended goal.
Outdated infrastructure (certainly not as much as in the US) has become a real problem for Germany.
In addition, the German leaders' budgetary frugality spills over the German borders and its effects are amplified by the monetary union, which does not have an exchange rate to accommodate national particularities.
Of course, the European Monetary Union is imperfect.
But turning the only institution ready to "do what needs to be done" to get the UEM back on track into a scapegoat is a very bad idea.
That countries would use, where it exists, the budgetary space they have at their disposal to ease the pressure on the ECB would be a much better strategy.
Germany, without a doubt, has a certain degree of maneuvering room in this regard.
